se’ (see   Bold   1) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Boulton","meanings":["English: variant of   Bolton  ."]},{"name":"Bold","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Staffordshire): from Middle English <i>bold</i> ‘dwelling-house’ (Old English <i>bold</i> the West Midland and northwestern form of Old English <i>bōthl</i>, <i>bōtl</i>), especially in the sense ‘castle or manor house’ for someone who lived or worked at the main house, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word, for example Bold (Lancashire), The Bold in Aston Botterell (Shropshire), Booden Farm in Haughton, Booth in Blithfield, and Bull Bridge in Penkridge (all Staffordshire). Compare   Bodle  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bold</i>, Old English <i>b(e)ald</i> ‘bold, brave, noble’, which in Middle English developed the additional sense ‘arrogant, impudent, shameless’.","English: variant of   Bolt   and possibly a variant of   Bald   2."]}]},{"name":"Oughtred","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the rare Old English personal name <i>Uhtrǣd</i>, composed of the elements <i>uht</i> ‘dawn’ + <i>rǣd</i> ‘counsel, advice’. This is a very uncommon given name in the English-speaking world, but remains in use in the Shuttleworth family."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Oughtred De Bolton was born in 1080, in Bowland, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Edwin de Bolton and Mrs Edwin de Bolton. He married De Mercia before 1135, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1155, in his hometown, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1080–1155":"1080–1155","1100–1160":"1100–1160","1135–1180":"1135–1180","1140–1226":"1140–1226","1060–1080":"1060–1080","–Female":"Surnud","1080":"1080","about 1140":"umbes 1140","after 1080":"pärast 1080","before 1135":"enne 1135","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1060":"1060","1180":"1180","1226":"1226","1135"